          "type": "paragraph",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>By March my heels were splitting. I'd been hiding them in socks at the gym, in closed-toe flats at the office, in sand at every beach trip. Drugstore foot creams felt like rubbing oil into concrete. A $40 callus shaver scraped raw skin without changing what was underneath. Even the salon pedicure — clinical, expensive, the supposed answer — peeled back into the same dryness within four days. <strong>Nothing reached the actual problem.</strong></p>"
          }
        },
        "p2": {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>A friend sent me a thirty-second video. A white sock-shaped pouch, milky liquid sealed inside, slipped over each foot for half an hour. A gentler alternative to the harsh peels — no burning, no salicylic acid, no five-day flake. I tried it that night, half-believing. The next morning I touched my heel before I got out of bed and felt <strong>skin instead of cracked plaster.</strong> Soft. For the first time in three years.</p>"
          }
